OMContract
Class Contract

java.lang.Object
  OMContract.Contract

public class Contract
extends java.lang.Object

Contract is a small framework that supports the design by contract pattern.

You can define preconditions, postconditions and invariants right in the line of code where they need to be checked. Each one of them throws his own Exception if the rules dont match, all of those Exceptions are subclasses of ContractExeption.

You can also turn checks on and off in your code to increase performance

Usage:

//This is a small sample of how to use Contract. Its really easy and intuitive.
class HowToUseContract {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(addWithoutContract(5, 13)); // output: 23
        System.out.println(addWithSimpleCheck(5, 13)); // output: 23
        System.out.println(addWithSimpleCheck(-1, 13));
//          output: OMContract.PreconditionFailedException: Precondition failed. Costum error message: No message specified
//                    at OMContract.Check.throwException(Check.java:92)
//                    at OMContract.Check.isTrue(Check.java:29)
//                    at OMContract.Assertion.isTrue(Assertion.java:64)
//                    at OMContract.HowToUseContract.addWithSimpleCheck(HowToUseContract.java:24)
//                    at OMContract.HowToUseContract.main(HowToUseContract.java:15)
        System.out.println(addWithMoreDetailedCheck(-1, 13));
        //output: OMContract.PreconditionFailedException: Precondition failed. Costum error message: both operands must be positive [...]
        System.out.println(addWithPostCondition(Integer.MAX_VALUE/2, Integer.MAX_VALUE/2+2));
//            output: -2147483648
//            OMContract.PostconditionFailedException: Postcondition failed. Costum error message: no overflow allowed
//            [...]

        try {
            System.out.println(addWithException(5, 13));
        } catch (PreconditionFailedException ex) {
            System.err.println("wrong operand found!");
        } catch (PostconditionFailedException ex) {
            System.err.println("too big");
        } catch (Exception ex) {
            System.out.println("no exception should reach here");
        }


//        You can also print to default outputstream with included check if Contract.isOn():
        Contract.out("This will only be printed if Contract is on");


    }

    private static int addWithoutContract(int op1, int op2){
        //This is how your methods looked so far
        return op1+op2;
    }

    private static int addWithSimpleCheck(int op1, int op2){
        //By callong Contract.precondition you define a precondition
        Contract.precondition()
                //Now you can make a chain of checks that need to be done
                .isTrue(op1 > 0)
                .isTrue(op2 > 0);
        //By default any failed checked will be prined to the error output.
        return op1+op2;
    }

    private static int addWithMoreDetailedCheck(int op1, int op2) {
        //In the generated error message you have seen you did not define a error message.
        //You can do that very simple:
        Contract.precondition()
                .errorMessage("both operands must be positive")
                .isTrue(op1 > 0)
                .isTrue(op2 > 0);
        return op1+op2;
    }

    private static int addWithMoreDetailedMessages(int op1, int op2) {
        //You can define error messages whenever you want. They will be used for
        //all upcoming checks in the current chain.
        Contract.precondition()
                .errorMessage("operand 1 must be positive")
                //You can check any comparable object for beeing in an inclusive range
                .isInInclusiveRange(1, Integer.MAX_VALUE, op1)
                .errorMessage("operand 2 must be positive")
                //You can also check it for beeing in an exklusive range
                //Note: if op2 was exactly Integer.MAX_VALUE the precondition would fail.
                //Thats not what we actually want here
                .isInExclusiveRange(0, Integer.MAX_VALUE, op2);
        return op1+op2;
    }

    private static int addWithPostCondition(int op1, int op2) {
        Contract.precondition()
                .errorMessage("both operands must be positive")
                .isTrue(op1 > 0)
                .isTrue(op2 > 0);
        int result = op1+op2;
        //Defining postconditions is just as easy:
        Contract.postcondition()
                .errorMessage("no overflow allowed")
                .isInInclusiveRange(1, Integer.MAX_VALUE, result);
        return result;
    }

    private static int addWithException(int op1, int op2) throws ContractException {
        //Sometimes its useful or necessary to throw an exception. You can do
        //this very easy: By telling Contract the following Checks are a
        //requirement it will throw PostconditionFailedException,
        //PreconditionFailedException or InvariantFailedException depending on the
        //contest in wich the check failed. Those 3 Exceptions inherit from ContractException
        //so they can be easily thrown or catched.
        Contract.requirement().precondition()
                .errorMessage("both operands must be positive")
                .isTrue(op1 > 0)
                .isTrue(op2 > 0);
        int result = op1+op2;
        //Defining postconditions is just as easy:
        Contract.requirement().postcondition()
                .errorMessage("no overflow allowed")
                .isInInclusiveRange(1, Integer.MAX_VALUE, result);
        return result;
    }

    private static int addWithExplicitAssertion(int op1, int op2) {
        //There are two more thing you have to learn about Contract:
        //There are two kinds of Checks: assertions and requirements
        //Assertions are the ones that are used by default, they will never
        //throw any ContractExceptions
        //Requirements are used for throwing Exceptions
        //You can tell Contract explicitly to use assertions if you want to make
        //your code easier to understand
        Contract.assertion()
                .invariant().errorMessage("Some useless check...")
                .isFalse(true);

        //Now here is the last lesson. Checking all kinds of stuff can be very
        //perfomance intensive. While you are in development that is no problem,
        //but often times you dont want all those checks in your production. So you
        //can swtich Contract on and off in any line of code:

        Contract.off();
        Contract.on();

        //You can also check if Contract is on if you want to make more complex
        //checks that cannot be put into one of Contracts standard methods.

        Contract.isOn();

        //To see all the standard methods go read the API.

        return op1+op2;
    }

}
